<article>
    <h1>Us&#xAD;ing cof&#xAD;fee busi&#xAD;ness to sup&#xAD;port women, youth</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201225/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-25"><time>2020-12-25</time></a>
        - <span>THE BIG STORY</span>
        - <span role="byline">PAMELA CHNG, BETTR BARISTA Goh Yan Han</span>
    </section>

    <p>At age 35, Ms Pamela Chng set out on a new ca­reer path.</p>
    <p>Un­like her pre­vi­ous pur­suits – such as run­ning a Web con­sul­tancy – Ms Chng’s new ven­ture was a so­cial en­ter­prise.</p>
    <p>The now 44-year-old founded Bettr Barista, a cof­fee com­pany which cham­pi­ons so­cially re­spon­si­ble prac­tices, in 2011.</p>
    <p>Ms Chng knew that she wanted to use her busi­ness as a force for good.</p>
    <p>Bettr Barista cur­rently runs a four-month pro­gramme for vul­ner­a­ble women and at-risk youth. It not only equips them with cof­fee-mak­ing skills, but also helps them build men­tal and emo­tional re­silience.</p>
    <p>Next month, the com­pany will roll out a two-month ac­cel­er­ated pro­gramme for in­di­vid­u­als with fewer sup­port needs than those who at­tend the four-month pro­gramme. They will get train­ing in gen­eral food and bev­er­age skills, and emo­tional health.</p>
    <p>Ms Chng is con­tin­u­ing to ex­pand her cof­fee busi­ness, as she looks into plans to branch out in Myan­mar, In­done­sia and the</p>
    <p>Philip­pines next year. Th­ese plans had been put on hold be­cause of the pan­demic.</p>
    <p>She is also in­tent on con­tin­u­ing to tackle the sys­temic is­sues in the cof­fee value chain, down to the farm­ers who grow the beans, and en­sur­ing in­dus­try prac­tices are more equal and in­clu­sive.</p>
    <p>She cred­its those around her for the suc­cess of Bettr Barista – from staff and cor­po­rate part­ners to so­cial or­gan­i­sa­tions and the Gov­ern­ment – which have sup­ported and col­lab­o­rated with the com­pany over the years.</p>
    <p>“We can’t change and help ev­ery­body, but ev­ery time I am strug­gling to make sense of why we con­tinue to do this very chal­leng­ing work, I get clearly re­minded by the progress I see in just one stu­dent.”</p>

